Economic Impact: Job Creation and Social Transformation
The development of a dedicated export channel to Malaysia would have significant multiplier effects on the Zambian economy, particularly in the underperforming agricultural sector.
Direct Employment Generation
The expansion of soybean production to meet a 60,000 MT annual export target would require a substantial increase in labor across the value chain.
On-Farm Labor: With smallholder yields targeted at 1.55 t/ha, 60,000 MT would require approximately 38,700 hectares of dedicated smallholder production. Given the labor-intensive nature of smallholder farming in Zambia, this could support thousands of seasonal and permanent agricultural jobs.
Aggregation and Logistics: GNA’s internal operations would need to expand, creating roles for data engineers, supply chain managers, and quality control technicians.
Transport and Forwarding: Moving 2,500 containers per year would significantly boost the Zambian trucking and freight forwarding sectors, supporting jobs in Lusaka and at the border crossings.
Value Chain Development and Ripple Effects
The introduction of soybeans into smallholder rotations provides critical soil health benefits. As a legume, soybeans fix nitrogen in the soil, reducing the need for expensive synthetic fertilizers for subsequent maize crops. This "soil amendment" effect increases the overall productivity of the farm, leading to improved food security and higher cumulative household income.
The income generated from these exports allows smallholder families to transition into the middle class, as envisioned by GNA. This transition manifests in increased local spending on education, healthcare, and consumer goods, stimulating the rural economy.
Policy, Compliance, and Regulatory Framework
Exporting to Malaysia requires strict adherence to international biosecurity standards and Malaysian domestic regulations.
The MAQIS and Department of Agriculture Requirements
All agricultural imports into Malaysia are governed by the Plant Quarantine Act 1976 and the Malaysian Quarantine and Inspection Services (MAQIS) Act 2011.
Import Permit (IP): The Malaysian importer must obtain an IP from MAQIS before the consignment leaves Zambia.
Phytosanitary Certificate (PC): The Zambian National Plant Protection Organization (NPPO) must issue a PC for every shipment, certifying that the goods are free from pests, diseases, and soil.
14-Day Rule: Consignments must be exported within fourteen days of the PC being issued.
Biosecurity Concerns: The Khapra Beetle
The Khapra Beetle (Trogoderma granarium) is a primary pest of concern for Malaysia. Although Zambia is not always listed as a high-risk country, the presence of the beetle in neighboring regions necessitates rigorous compliance.
Consignments must be free from Khapra Beetle and other regulated articles like weed seeds and plant debris. If a country is designated as a target-risk country, mandatory fumigation is required:
Methyl Bromide (MB): 80 g/m^3 for 48 hours at \ge 21^\circ\text{C}.
Phosphine (PH_3): 5 g/m^3 for 120 hours.
All treatments must be conducted by accredited service providers registered with the NPPO.
Post-Entry Quarantine (PEQ)
Upon arrival in Malaysia, MAQIS officers will conduct visual inspections and may take samples for laboratory analysis at the National Post Entry Quarantine Station in Serdang. If quarantine pests are detected, the Department of Agriculture has the right to suspend future importations from the source until the issue is rectified.
Tariffs and Taxation Environment
The financial feasibility of Zambian exports is influenced by the trade agreements and domestic taxes applicable in Malaysia.
Import Duties and MFN Status
Zambia and Malaysia trade under Most Favored Nation (MFN) terms as WTO members. Historically, Malaysia has applied a 0\% import duty on whole soybeans (HS Code 1201.90) to support its domestic feed industry.
Sales and Service Tax (SST) Expansion
In July 2025, Malaysia implemented an expansion of its SST framework.
Applied Rate: While "essential" goods remained at 0\%, many agricultural commodities, including soybeans, were moved to a 5\% sales tax bracket.
Impact on Exporters: This tax is typically paid by the importer at the point of entry but is calculated based on the CIF value plus duties.
